    <body>

        <div xml:id="AN178.2-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">tōḻi varaivu malintu colliyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">What the confidante said when rejoicing of the marriage.</p>
        </div>
        <div xml:id="AN178.2">
      <lg type="edition">
        <l>vayirat taṉṉa vaiyēntu maruppiṉ</l>
        <l>vetirvē raṉṉa parumayi<supplied>rp</supplied> paṉṟi</l>
        <l>paṟaikka ṇaṉṉa niṟaiccuṉai paruki</l>
        <l>nīlat ta<supplied>ṉ</supplied>ṉa vakalilaic cēmpiṉ</l>
        <l>piṇṭa maṉṉa koḻuṅkiḻaṅku māntip</l>
        <l>piṭimaṭin taṉṉa kaṉmicai yūḻiḻi</l>
        <l>piyāṟucērn taṉṉa vūṟunīrp paṭāarp</l>
        <l>paimputa ṉaḷicimaik kurukirun taṉṉa</l>
        <l>vaṇpiṇi yaviḻnta veṇkū tāḷat</l>
        <l>talaṅkukulai yalari <supplied>tī</supplied>ṇṭi viṉainar</l>
        <l>poṉṉuraik kaṭṭa<supplied>ḷai</supplied> kaṭuppak kāṉavar</l>
        <l>kiḷaiyamal ciṟutiṉai viḷakuraṉ mēyntu</l>
        <l>kaṇṇiṉitu paṭukku naṉmalai nāṭaṉoṭu</l>
        <l>puṇarntaṉai puṇarnta nīyu niṉṟōṭ</l>
        <l>paṇaikkavi ṉaḻiyātu tuṇaippuṇarn teṉṟun</l>
        <l><supplied>ta</supplied>vali lulakat tuṟaiyarō tōḻi</l>
        <l><supplied>ye</supplied>llaiyu miravu meṉṉātu kalleṉak</l>
        <l>koṇṭal vāṉam poḻinta vaikaṟait</l>
        <l>taṇpaṉi yaṟciran tamiyōrk kariteṉak</l>
        <l>kaṉaviṉum piriyala ravarē yataṉṟalai</l>
        <l>muṟṟāṉ kaṇṭa ñāṉṟiṉum</l>
        <l>piṟperi taḷikkun paṇpi ṉāṉē.</l>
      </lg>
      <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
        <l>With the man from the land of good mountains, where (13cd)</l>
        <l>the pigs with hair coarse like bamboo roots (2)</l>
        <l>[and] sharp upright tusks like clubs (1)</l>
        <l>drink from mountain pools full like the eyes of drums, (3)</l>
        <l>feed on the rich bulbous roots like on lumps of rice (5)</l>
        <l>of the Cēmpu with leaves broad like [those of] the blue lotus, (4)</l>
        <l>descend in turn from the height of boulders that are like dozing elephant cows, (6)</l>
        <l>to the low bushes with water drizzling as if from a river, (7)</l>
        <l>grip the flowers on the swaying bunches (10a-c)</l>
        <l>of the white Convolvulus that had opened [its] generous outer petals, (9)</l>
        <l>like herons perched on the dense summits of fresh bushes, (8)</l>
        <l>graze on the ripening ears of the thickly branching little millet (12)</l>
        <l>of the forest people, resembling the gold-grating touch stones of workmen, (11)</l>
        <l rend="indent8">[and] pleasantly closes [its] eyes, (13ab)</l>
        <l>you have united, you who united [with him], and, always being united</l>
        <l>with [your] mate, without your shoulder losing [its] bamboo beauty, (14f.)</l>
        <l>won’t he come [and] stay in an undiminishing world, friend? (16)</l>
        <l>Since the season of cool dew is difficult for those who are alone, (19)</l>
        <l>at cold dawn when the clouds have showered [their] wealth (18)</l>
        <l>noisily, without heeding day or night, (17)</l>
        <l>he won’t part [from you] anymore than a dream. Moreover, (20)</l>
        <l>more than in the time he has seen [you] before (21)</l>
        <l>he is of a nature to take well care [of you] later on. (22)</l>
      </lg>
